{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598272"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:35:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15453"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15453"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61830"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8144"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15453"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47276"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19932"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61830"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of abdominal pain, bloody diarrhoea, and weight loss of 5 kg. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the right lower quadrant without peritonism. Digital rectal examination reveals no masses but blood on the glove. Colonoscopy is performed and there are no abnormal findings until the transverse colon is reached (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ulcerative colitis","Crohn disease","Infectious colitis","Ischaemic colitis","Diverticulitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe endoscopic image shows deep, serpiginous ulcers with intervening normal mucosa creating a cobblestone appearance, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E. The presence of skip lesions (areas of normal mucosa between affected areas) and the depth of ulceration are key distinguishing features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlcerative colitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows continuous inflammation starting from the rectum, with a friable mucosa, superficial ulceration, and absence of skip lesions. The cobblestone appearance and deep ulcers seen here would be unusual. The colonoscopic finding of a normal distal colon and rectum would exclude this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious colitis\u003C/strong\u003E, such as that caused by \u003Cem\u003EClostridium difficile\u003C/em\u003E or other bacterial pathogens, typically presents more acutely and shows diffuse erythema with pseudomembranes or superficial ulceration rather than the deep ulcers seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic colitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects watershed areas such as the splenic flexure and typically shows segmental distribution with sharp demarcation between affected and normal mucosa. The pattern of ulceration would be different. Ischaemic colitis is most typically found in older patients who have co-existing vascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show diverticular outpouchings with surrounding inflammation, rather than the linear ulcers and cobblestoning pattern seen here. It would be an unlikely finding in a 25-year-old patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s age, presentation with chronic symptoms, and the characteristic endoscopic findings make Crohn disease the most likely diagnosis. Additional features supporting this diagnosis include the right-sided abdominal pain and weight loss. Further workup would include biopsies, imaging to assess disease extent, and blood tests to evaluate inflammatory markers and nutritional status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopic findings of deep, serpiginous ulcers with cobblestoning are characteristic of Crohn disease.","Skip lesions and transmural inflammation distinguish Crohn disease from ulcerative colitis endoscopically.","Crohn disease can affect any part of the gastrointestinal tract from mouth to anus."],"references":["\u0022CD colitis\u0022 by Kauczuk is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:CD_colitis.jpg","Cai Z, Wang S, Li J. Treatment of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Comprehensive Review. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Dec 20;8:765474. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2021.765474. PMID: 34988090; PMCID: PMC8720971","McDowell C, Farooq U, Haseeb M. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262182","Fakhoury M, Negrulj R, Mooranian A, Al-Salami H. Inflammatory bowel disease: clinical aspects and treatments. J Inflamm Res. 2014 Jun 23;7:113-20. doi: 10.2147/JIR.S65979. PMID: 25075198; PMCID: PMC4106026","Tavakoli P, Vollmer-Conna U, Hadzi-Pavlovic D, Grimm MC. A Review of Inflammatory Bowel Disease: A Model of Microbial, Immune and Neuropsychological Integration. Public Health Rev. 2021 May 5;42:1603990. doi: 10.3389/phrs.2021.1603990. PMID: 34692176; PMCID: PMC8386758","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47276"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21162"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21162"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RIg6yDeondkqCTnWDk8MCdTYzAM2DV.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RIg6yDeondkqCTnWDk8MCdTYzAM2DV.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":448,"height":384}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47276"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T15:35:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T15:36:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8144"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61830"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine",